This is a model of a face-centered cubic unit cell showing how partial atoms are included in the unit cell proper.  The intended purpose of this thing is to use in a chemistry or materials classroom so that students can see the 3-dimensional aspects of the crystal structure.  One possible use of this thing is to print multiples of this model so that they can be stacked to show how unit cells add together to generate an extended lattice.

I printed this with 2 shells and a 10% infill with a raft.  The model includes support structures at local minima that need to be trimmed away after printing (I used wire cutters).  The spheres are well connected by themselves (I put cylinders between them to increase the contact area).

title: QU-BD OneUp/TwoUp Extruder Body (E3D+Anubis+MK8 Drive Gear)

description.text: UPDATE 1: Updated to support the original QU-BD Anubis hotend. I have been using ddegonge888's extruder design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:296670) on my OneUp for a while, and I can't say enough good things about it. I've been considering making the switch to the MK8 drive gear, and so I modified his design to work with the MK8. The MK8 itself has a much smaller drive diameter, and so I had to make quite a few changes to the extruder design itself. It also works with the original lever arms, so if you've already printed his original extruder design, the only thing you need to do to be MK8 compatible is print the main body! I've also modified the tensioner screw to sit slightly angled, as it will provide better tensioning capability when higher tension is needed. As of right now, I only built it with the E3D in mind but I've modified it to include Anubis support. Just download the body files for your specific hotend. As per the usual, both SolidWorks and STL files are included. Enjoy!

description.text:
This thing has been inspired by thing:707024 but it has been totally rewritten from scratch, using a different approach. It has also been improved with new features like the capability to add layers so 3D puzzles can be created. The number of blocks and layers are only limited by the amount of available memory of your computer. The following parameters can be defined by the user:
  • Size (refers to the unit basic block dimensions)
  • Gaps
  • Radius
  • Box thickness
  • Number of rows
  • Number of columns
  • Number of layers
  • Shapes easily configurable by coordinates, so you can make your own puzzle design. See further details in the source scad file.

STL example files are provided for 7x9x1 and 5x6x2.
Scad files are provided so you can create your own design. Please, follow the instructions inside the scad file to learn how to define your own shaped blocks. STL files designed with more than 1 layer may need an additional step for splitting the individual parts before printing them. The box to keep all the parts together is created automatically to your dimensions along with your design. Two identical half shells fit perfectlly to keep your parts safe from being lost. I used a simple elastic band to keep them closed. Printed with 3 bottom and top layers, 25% infill, no supports.

description.text: Its a Diver, a popper, or even a bobber. No need to attach a hook to the lure. Clip the lure on your line and you are ready to go. If the bill of the penguin is towards the hook, it will pop, if the feet are toward the hook, it will dive. You can also put stink bait in the lure!

This lure is two parts that clip together. Bottom and Top. The bottom has a diamond on it.  
To Dive: Run line on top of the bill and straight to the feet. Go through both holes and tie on your line. Clip on the top and you are ready to go.  
To Pop: Run the line through the bottom foots hole and over the top of the second hole (don't go through the second hole, you want your line to be clipped in) and then down through the last hole towards the bill. Tie your hook. Clip on the top and fish away  
To Bob: Just clip it on where you want!  
*Only tested with ABS plastic, and a treble hook.  
**You may have to sand the two notches on the clip down a tad bit depending on how your printer prints them. I have only had to sand one out of four models.

title: Ducto de ventilación de Catnozzle v.2.3 para impresión con filamentos PLA y TPU

description.text: Este ducto de ventilación lo hemos diseñado para mejorar la impresión de filamentos PLA y TPU en el hotend Catnozzle v.2.3 evitando la obstrucción y los problemas de extrusión.Utiliza un ventilador de 40mm.

materiales:
2 tornillos M3 de 25mm
2 tornillos M3 de 15mm
1 ducto de ventilación
1 soporte para ducto de ventilación
1 ventilador de 40mm
1 tuerca M4
1 arandela para tornillo M4
instrucciones:
1) Imprimir el ducto y soporte de ventilación.
2) Fijar el ventilador 40mm al ducto de ventilación y al soporte con los tornillos M3 de 25mm colocando las arandelas en contacto con la parte externa del soporte.
3) Terminar de fijar el ventilador con los tornillos M3 de 15mm
4) Sujetar el conjunto al cuerpo del extrusor utilizando el tornillo M4 que fija el hotend, fijar con arandela y tuerca M4.
Observaciones:
Centrar el ducto con respecto al hotend.

title: Home Depot "Cut Ticket" Notebook Holder #RetailTools UPDATED 2015-05-11

description.text:
This video shows how it works: https://youtu.be/mIeqnrG8qjM At my job at Home Depot, I cut products such as wire and use "cut tickets" to record the information. The only problem, as every Home Depot employee knows, is that the tickets all come unglued, leaving a mess of paper in my apron. The solution is this "cut ticket" holder, which secures the tickets and provides a cover. You can also affix helpful information to the surfaces, such as a store map, department extensions, etc.
.
This is designed for notepads measuring 140mm x 108mm. You can use Sketchup to modify the files to fit your particular-sized notepad. (Lowes, Hobby Lobby, Wal-Mart, etc.) The holes on top are intended for a zip tie hook. Run a zip tie through the holes to form a hanger. Then hook a carabiner to the zip tie. I recommend a layer height of .2mm. I printed mine in a nice Home Depot orange. Snap together and glue if desired. You'll notice a diagonal edge on the rectangular top piece, and that just needs to align with the edge on the hinged piece. This is an improvement over the stock isolators to better compensate for any skew of the Z nut. description.text:
Make your own set (91 pieces) of domino's to cut in with a laser cutter.
which also includes the files for a set of rules (Danish and English), 8 player pieces and a "created by" block to make the number of pieces fit neatly in a box. Also check out this laser cut box that holds a set of domino including the rule block:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:714648

Preparing the files: If you just want to make the premade set that I uploaded then just skip the rest of this step (Mexican train - Flora.ai).
If you want to generate your own set then just complete the following steps: Find an image that you want for the "dots" on the pieces and prepare it for engraving (see flora.ai)
Open the excel and search and replace the "exactPath" with the path for your image
Export the excel as a Text (tab delimited) file
Open the inDesign file and adjust the size of the page to fit your cutting piece
Relink the data merge file in the inDesign file with the new file you made
Now use the data merge function to generate your domino's
If you want to customise it more than this then make your desired changes in the master page. The 8 player piece should be visually different, and should therefore be made individually, mine was made by adding a number and rotating the flora image used. The "created by" even though not needed should be made so that all the piece fits in layers of 8 pieces for example in a box like this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:714648 Finally the simplified rules are made in both danish and english and can be found in the Train rules file. Preparing to cut: Choose the material that you want to use.
Cover it in masking tape to prevent the gas created when cutting to color the pieces.
Create: Cut the pieces with the appropriate amount of Pew Pew

title: Mini filament holder for Flashforge Dreamer

description.text:
When you buy some filaments, especially pricier ones that come in smaller quantities, they sometimes come without a spool. Some spools are too large to fit inside on the filament mount - and once you've used a good chunk of it, still having a giant honking spool is an annoyance. I wanted a spool that was easy and fairly quick to load and which would store compactly (my Dreamer lives on my sailboat - and space is always at a premium on boats).  
This spool is built to hang on the internal spool mount for the Dreamer but will probably work for others with little or no modification.

Since I needed a spool, and wanted a nice compact one, I drew one up and printed it. This spool prints in two pieces - printing as a single piece would take many times as much time on most filament printers because of the amount of support needed.  
I glued mine together with Loctite Plastic Bonder. They slide together and align easily because of the notched center of the spindle.  
The photo shows about 1/8kg of Laywoo-d3 on one mounted in the Dreamer. The included ".c4d" file is the Cinema4D scene file that I designed the spool in.
